description: 2-Methoxyphencyclidine (2-MeO-PCP) is a dissociative hallucinogen of the arylcyclohexylamine class. Based on structure-activity relationship studies, it has lower affinity for the NMDA receptor compared to 3-MeO-PCP, which has been demonstrated to have the highest affinity of the three isomeric anisyl-substitutions of PCP, followed by 2-MeO-PCP and 4-MeO-PCP. Limited peer-reviewed data exists on its specific pharmacology, metabolism, and toxicity profile.
contraindications: History of psychosis, cardiovascular conditions, liver disease
interactions: MAOIs, stimulants, other dissociatives, alcohol, benzodiazepines
toxicity_profile: Limited specific data available, but likely similar to other arylcyclohexylamines with risks of hypertension, tachycardia, confusion, and psychosis

description: 3-Methyl-PCP is a dissociative anesthetic of the arylcyclohexylamine class that is structurally related to phencyclidine (PCP). Based on its structural similarity to 3-MeO-PCE and 3-HO-PCP, it is assumed to have high affinity for the NMDA receptor and likely inhibits reuptake of norepinephrine and dopamine, causing dissociative effects. Limited toxicological and pharmacological data is available, with only one reported toxicology case identified by the Center for Forensic Science Research and Education.

description: 3-Methoxyphencyclidine morpholine (3-MeO-PCMo) is a dissociative anesthetic drug which is similar in structure to phencyclidine (PCP) but features a morpholine ring instead of piperidine. Research has shown it has significantly lower potency as an NMDA receptor antagonist compared to PCP and 3-MeO-PCP, with an IC50 value of 26.67 μM (versus 2.02 μM for PCP and 1.51 μM for 3-MeO-PCP). This suggests approximately 13-18 times lower potency at the NMDA receptor compared to related compounds.

toxicity_profile: Limited specific data available, but likely similar though weaker than other arylcyclohexylamines

description: 4-Methoxyphencyclidine morpholine (4-MeO-PCMo) is a dissociative anesthetic of the arylcyclohexylamine class featuring a morpholine ring instead of piperidine and a methoxy group at the 4-position. By analogy to the reduced potency of 4-MeO-PCP compared to 3-MeO-PCP, and the reduced potency of PCMo analogs compared to PCP analogs, it is likely to have substantially reduced potency compared to traditional dissociatives. Very limited scientific data exists for this compound.

description: 4-Methoxyphencyclidine (4-MeO-PCP) is a dissociative anesthetic of the arylcyclohexylamine class that was the first dissociative research chemical to appear on the market in 2008. It has been established to have lower binding affinity for the NMDA receptor compared to both 3-MeO-PCP and 2-MeO-PCP, making it less potent. Users have reported oral doses typically between 50-100 mg, confirming its reduced potency. Limited case reports of intoxication exist, including cases from Sweden (2015) and Korea (2019).
